        \subsubsection{Phonetic variants}
          While Table \ref{tab:pronouns_attested} includes many equivalent subject pronouns that have been attested, the list expands significantly when including allomorphs and phonetic variants that have been attested.
          Although the current study will not carry out any analyses of phonetic variation in subject pronouns, an overview will help to clarify some coding decisions that will be discussed in section \ref{sec:pronoun_coding}.
    
          The morpheme \lexi{je}, which in Louisiana has only attested as a first person singular subject pronoun, has received significant attention in the literature.
          The two segments of this morpheme often metathesize (\citeauthor{brown_pronominal_1988}, \citeyear[p.~141]{brown_pronominal_1988}; \citeauthor{parr_glossary_1940}, \citeyear[p.~xi]{parr_glossary_1940}), to the extent that the metathesized form is sometimes the only form provided in grammars \parencite[pp.~31-32]{chaudoir_study_1938}.
          The vowel, [ə], can be elided not only before vowels \parencite[p.~193]{oukada_louisiana_1977} but also before consonants (\citeauthor{phillips_spoken_1939}, \citeyear[pp.~218-219]{phillips_spoken_1939}; \citeauthor{smith_morphosyntactic_1994}, \citeyear[p.~43]{smith_morphosyntactic_1994}).
          The appearance of the vowel has been argued to be only for ``clarity or emphasis'' \parencite[p.~141]{conwell_louisiana_1963}.
          This results in the consonant, which can be realized as [ʒ], [ʃ], [z], [s], or [h] \parencite[p.~72]{carmichael_language_2019}, being adjacent to the initial segment of the following word.
          There is thus a clear phonological rule that applies to this particular morpheme where [ʒ] and [z] are devoiced before voiceless segments (\citeauthor{papen_structural_1997}, \citeyear[p.~82]{papen_structural_1997}; \citeauthor{phillips_etude_1936}, \citeyear[p.~42]{phillips_etude_1936}; \citeauthor{rottet_language_1995}, \citeyear[pp.~127/176]{rottet_language_1995}; \citeauthor{smith_morphosyntactic_1994}, \citeyear[p.~43]{smith_morphosyntactic_1994}), as in Rule \ref{phonorule:pro_devoicing}.
          Of the remaining forms, there is a more general variation between [ʒ] and [h] where either can variably appear in the same position in any morpheme.
          This is not the case, however, for [z], which is only in variation with [ʒ] in the pronoun \lexi{je} \parencite[p.~121]{dajko_ethnic_2009}.
          While one could possibly argue that [z] and [ʒ] represent two distinct morphemes based on this, \citeauthor{dajko_ethnic_2009}'s (\citeyear{dajko_ethnic_2009}) data shows [z] in stylistic variation with [ʒ], suggesting individual speakers use both variants.
          It is certainly not out of the question that an individual could use two different subject pronouns for the same referent, but this seems less likely when the sole difference is a slight change in place of articulation.
          The evidence suggests then that all of these realizations are variants of one subject pronoun morpheme: \lexi{je}.
    
