          \end{enumerate}
          
          Also used exclusively for first person singular reference are the forms [mo], [mwa], [mɔ̃], and [mwɛ̃].
          Generally described as a subject pronoun used in Creole, it has also been attested in Terrebonne-Lafourche (\citeauthor{gudmestad_variationist_2022}, \citeyear[p.~11]{gudmestad_variationist_2022}; \citeauthor{rottet_language_1995}, \citeyear[p.~178]{rottet_language_1995}) and Vermilion Parish (BRANDON 1955) where it is given as \orth{mon} or \orth{moi}, presumably the [mɔ̃] and [mwa] realizations, respectively, rather than the typically attested [mo] or [mwɛ̃] realizations in Creole.
          None of these parishes have been noted for having creolophone residents, diminishing the possibility for influence between speech varieties despite the resemblances.
          Indeed, progressive nasalization as a general phonological process has been noted as a distinguishing trait of Creole \parencite[p.~53]{neumann_creole_1985}, which would render [mo] as [mɔ̃] when present.
          From the opposite direction, the morpheme has been documented as reducing to [m] before vowels in the speech of francophones \parencite[p.~178]{rottet_language_1995}, just as is typical in Creole (\citeauthor{broussard_louisiana_1972}, \citeyear[p.~8]{broussard_louisiana_1972}; \citeauthor{klingler_if_2003}, \citeyear[pp.~209-210]{klingler_if_2003}; \citeauthor{neumann_creole_1985}, \citeyear[pp.~95-96]{neumann_creole_1985}; \citeauthor{phillips_etude_1936}, \citeyear[p.~43]{phillips_etude_1936}).
          In Terrebonne-Lafourche where \lexi{je} can be pronounced as [h], this raises the possibility that speakers are actually producing a variant of \lexi{moi} followed by a barely audible [h] rather than simply \lexi{moi} by itself.
          Given that voiceless fricatives are likely less audible than voiced fricatives \parencite[p.~117]{maniwa_perception_2008}, such a result would not be surprising, although one must assume that the coding methods employed by previous researchers would have accounted for potentially inaudible tokens.
          Alternatively, in St Landry Parish where French and Creole are in heavy contact, \lexi{moi} without \lexi{je} was also attested in what was otherwise characterized as French speech \parencite{dubois_attrition_2001}.
          While it is more difficult to rule the influence of Creole in this last case, meaning it is also more difficult to rule out whether each phonetic variant is socially interpreted differently without conducting a variationist study of them.
          In the absence of such a study, and given their obviously shared origin in the disjunctive pronoun \lexi{moi} and similar phonological behavior, they can perhaps be treated as equivalents, and in the case of the present study, no tokens of [mwa] nor [mwɛ̃] were found, therefore simplifying the issue.
          % Among Indians in Terrebonne-Lafourche, moi for 1sg was more likely before a vowel (Gudmestad & Carmichael 2022:18)
          % 1sg as [h] among Indians in Terrebonne-Lafourche more frequent before vowels (Rottet 1996, as cited in Gudmestad & Carmichael 2022:5)
          % Elision of the vowel in mo is possible before consonants as long as not preceded by another consonant (Klingler 2003 "Turn":210)
          % In the early 20th century, moi je was more common that je by itself in Evangeline Parish, presumably because Creole was in close contact with "Cajun" at that time (Phillips 1936, as cited in Rottet 1995:181)
    
          The form pairs [nu] - [no] and [vu] - [vo] present similar problems of interpretation but with a different results.
          The first realization for each pair has been found in both French-oriented and Creole-oriented speech but with different behaviors.
          In Terrebonne-Lafourche \parencite[pp.~190-191]{oukada_louisiana_1977}, where Creole is not present, [nu] generates a [z] liaison when followed by a vowel, just as one finds in Hexagonal French.
          The same was found in Lafayette for both [nu] and [vu] \parencite[pp.~142-143]{conwell_louisiana_1963}.
          In Creole-oriented speech, however, such an environment leads to a reduction of [nu] to [n] and [vu] to [v] \parencite[p.~8]{broussard_louisiana_1972}, something which is even possible before consonants for [nu] for some speakers \parencite[pp.~209-210]{klingler_if_2003}.
          This difference in behavior might suggest that speakers have different morpheme targets in their mental grammars or at least different morphophonemic rules, perhaps \lexi{nous} and \lexi{vous} versus \lexi{nou} and \lexi{vou}.
          What is more important here, though, is whether speakers treat these as distinct pronouns as that would allow them to be socially interpreted differently.
          Two factors support the idea that they are treated as distinct.
          The first is that Creole-oriented speakers may alternate between [nu] and [no] as well as [vu] and [vo] \parencite[p.~24c]{morgan_structural_1959}, whereas French-oriented speakers do not, phonetically distinguishing \lexi{nous} - \lexi{nou} and \lexi{vous} - \lexi{vou} to a greater degree.
          This was in fact the case for one speaker in my own corpus who produced both [nu] and [no].
          This is admittedly a weak argument for treating these as different pronouns.
          The factor that provides a stronger argument for a distinction is the inflection morphology used for verbs
